                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Twizlewink wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The danger comes from the fact that Canadian perscriptions have to be perscribed by a Canadian doctor. Most poeple who are ordering drugs in the internet are not consulting with a doctor in person, and that's an added level of risk. So it's unsafe for that reason, which is legitimate imo.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I disagree. Most of the people buying medicines from across the border are buying the same exact prescription drugs in the same dosages that they would get from within the US borders. Sure, a Canadian doctor didn't prescribe the medicine but it was prescribed by a licensed doctor. That's assuming you're not just prescribing your own medicines...which is an idiotic thing to do and a whole different can of worms which isn't relevant to the purchase of prescribed medicines from a licensed doctor. 
<br />

<br />
There are many prescriptions filled online in the US and that doesn't change regardless of whether the pharmacy is within the US border or not. You're getting the same exact medicines which are made by the same exact companies and possibly from the same batch as that shipping from both borders. 
<br />

<br />
Wolja brings up a legitimate IMHO point to an increase in price for medicines in the US is the very very high prices in insurance for practitioners in the medical field. It's getting so bad that in certain states like Pennsylvania (where I live) a lot of medical practioners are moving out of the state simply because they can't afford to pay the insurance required to practice medicine. 
<br />

<br />
The other big thing are the extra tests required by the FDA before medicines can be sold within US borders. But as anyone who knows, unless the tests are done by an impartial party and not by the company marketing the drug, it can be shown to be as safe as they want it to be (within reason). 
<br />

<br />
