                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Twizlewink wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Hikaru wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">That's assuming you're not just prescribing your own medicines...which is an idiotic thing to do and a whole different can of worms which isn't relevant to the purchase of prescribed medicines from a licensed doctor.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
But it's certainly relevant to purchasing medications across the border, because safeguards are not in place to prevent this. It's the potential for abuse that is a serious health concern and can be abused wholesale by the unethical. Lets not forget that some drugs are legal for medical use here that are not in the US and vice versa, pot probably being the most obvious. Canadians can purchase drugs more inexpensively because the government makes it happen for us, and there is no reason that the US can't have the same thing if they want it, but they don't because it hurts profits and for some incredible reason that's more important then quality of life to the majority of voting Americans.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The idea is, profits from drugs provide incentive (and funds) to research drugs.  So, the amount of profit going to drug companies determines how many drugs will be availiable in the future.
<br />

<br />
So, you support high drug prices now, in exchange for better (and still expensive) drugs tommorrow.  In theory, after 15-odd years, the drug patent runs out, and the public recieves the 'good' for the higher drug prices it paid.
<br />

<br />
Theoretically, it should work.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
